-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Barclays Bank Kenya, Unilever Ghana Are Active
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   M o s e s   M o z a r t   D z a w u
-- 2010-11-22T15:28:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-barclays-bank-kenya-unilever-ghana.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  fell the
most in a year, dropping 2.6 percent to 82.35 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  fell for a third day, retreating
0.5 percent to 1,909.92 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis.
Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  slipped 0.2 percent to
840.05 by the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange
All-Share Index  retreated 0.1 percent to 6,994.57 by the 2 p.m.
close in Accra, the first decline in five days.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Barclays Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (BCBL KN), the nation’s largest
lender by market value, gained the most since Nov. 4, adding 50
cents, or 0.8 percent, to 63.5 shillings. Profit for the nine
months through September climbed 20 percent to 5.5 billion
shillings ($69 million), Barclays said on Nov. 19.  Unilever Ghana Ltd.  (UNIL GN), Unilever Plc’s unit in the
West African nation added 5 pesewas, or 0.9 percent, to 5.6
cedis, the highest since Sept. 23. “Investors expect the
company’s revenue to improve further as we draw to the
yuletide,” said Emmanuel Tsigbey, a broker at Renaissance
Capital, said in a phone interview from Accra. “For the whole
year, we expect revenue to climb between 10 and 15 percent over
last year’s."  To contact the reporters on this story:
